11:18.644 --> 11:24.350 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We will remain there in the
north, basically
in the north of Afghanistan,
where we have

11:24.383 --> 11:26.252 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the largest force.

11:26.285 --> 11:32.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we will stay there and do
the job to stabilize
Afghanistan, so that it doesn't
fall back

11:32.825 --> 11:35.361 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
into conflict and turmoil.

11:35.394 --> 11:39.465 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Different
subject, the Paris
climate accord.

11:39.498 --> 11:44.970 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As I know you are aware, there
have been reports
today all day long that
President Trump is

11:45.004 --> 11:50.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
close to making a decision, and
that he is
leaning toward the United States
pulling out

11:50.810 --> 11:51.911 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of the accord.

11:51.944 --> 11:53.979 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If that happened, what would the
repercussions
be?

11:54.013 --> 12:00.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER WITTIG: Well, first of
all, as we speak,
we don't know what the decision
will be.

12:00.953 --> 12:06.792 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's no secret we have been a
staunch advocate
of the Paris agreement.

12:06.826 --> 12:10.963 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We think it's a landmark
achievement.

12:10.996 --> 12:19.939 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's an almost universal
agreement containing
the global warming, fighting
climate change.

12:19.972 --> 12:26.078 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we think it's so important
that the U.S.
stays on board in a leadership
role.

12:26.112 --> 12:32.418 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Thanks to the U.S., this
agreement was possible
in the first place.

12:32.451 --> 12:38.691 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, if the U.S. would leave,
you know, it
would be a kind of
self-isolation, and the

12:38.724 --> 12:45.498 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
U.S. would find itself in odd
company, just
with Syria and Nicaragua, the
only countries

12:45.531 --> 12:48.701 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that are not part of the Paris
agreement.

12:48.734 --> 12:50.503 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we don't think that's a good
option.

12:50.536 --> 12:54.406 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Let me read you
something now
that we just learned.

12:54.440 --> 12:59.111 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is the European Commission
president,
Jean-Claude Juncker.

12:59.145 --> 13:01.380 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He had a message for President
Trump.

13:01.413 --> 13:06.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He said in Germany -- he said,
"Mr. Trump
believes that the U.S. can leave
the agreement"

13:07.019 --> 13:09.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- and I'm quoting him -- he
said, "because
he said he doesn't get close
enough to the

13:09.789 --> 13:12.525 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
dossiers to fully understand
them."

13:12.558 --> 13:14.360 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He went on.

13:14.393 --> 13:18.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He said: "We tried to explain
that to Mr.
Trump in Taormina," where the
meetings were,

13:18.264 --> 13:20.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
"in clear German sentences.

13:20.566 --> 13:22.701 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It seems our attempt failed."

13:22.735 --> 13:25.604 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Does the president understand
this issue,
do you believe?

13:25.638 --> 13:34.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER WITTIG: Well, I think he
has advisers
that explain that to him, and I
trust that

13:34.380 --> 13:40.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he will be fully briefed by his
advisers on
the importance of that
agreement.

13:40.252 --> 13:46.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't doubt that there is the
expertise
of the White House to judge on
the merits

13:46.692 --> 13:48.894 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of that Paris agreement.

13:48.928 --> 13:57.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We just hope that it will not
lead to major
repercussions for this global
achievement

13:57.970 --> 13:59.805 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that we think Paris is.

13:59.839 --> 14:05.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, of course,
it wasn't only
the Paris accord that came up
during the G7

14:05.244 --> 14:10.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
summit and even during the NATO
conversations,
but it looked as if to the
outside world that

14:10.883 --> 14:14.119 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
this was a strained series of
meetings.

14:14.153 --> 14:18.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the aftermath of it, your own
chancellor
had remarks over the last few
days in which

14:18.624 --> 14:23.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
she said -- and I'm quoting
again -- she said:
"The times in which we,"
referring to Europe,

14:24.029 --> 14:28.267 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
"could completely rely on others
are over
to a certain extent."

14:28.300 --> 14:32.104 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She said, "This is what I
experienced in the
last few days."

14:32.137 --> 14:33.873 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What is she saying?

14:33.906 --> 14:39.111 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER WITTIG: Well, Judy, I
think, you know,
Chancellor Merkel has a good and
productive

14:39.144 --> 14:42.314 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
relationship with President
Trump.

14:42.348 --> 14:46.685 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have met in Washington and
now in Europe.

14:46.719 --> 14:53.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have been on the phone on a
whole range
of issues of the international
agenda.

14:53.158 --> 15:01.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the chancellor has been
committed to transatlantic
relations, to a friendship with
the U.S. right

15:01.634 --> 15:05.971 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from the start of her career as
few other
leaders have been.

15:06.005 --> 15:11.977 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, she is a staunch believer in
close relations
with the U.S., and that doesn't
change with

15:12.011 --> 15:13.512 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the president.

15:13.545 --> 15:19.752 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What she said is -- and I think
that is, you
know, a call on the Europeans.

15:19.785 --> 15:22.121 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And she has said this before.

15:22.154 --> 15:26.358 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We cannot leave our fate in the
hand of others.

15:26.392 --> 15:29.295 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have to take it in our own
hands.

15:29.328 --> 15:38.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have got to push European
reform forward,
and it's us who have to
determine the future

15:38.103 --> 15:39.838 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of Europe.

15:39.872 --> 15:42.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But she is saying
this as a
result of the new policies of
and approach

15:42.908 --> 15:44.576 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of President Trump, correct?

15:44.610 --> 15:49.048 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PETER WITTIG: We have excellent
relations
to the United States.

15:49.081 --> 15:50.716 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
We always have.

15:50.749 --> 15:56.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And part of those relations is
precisely that
you can also discuss
divergences.

15:56.789 --> 16:05.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this is what happened in
Europe where
they discussed points where they
diverge.

16:05.064 --> 16:06.498 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They have differences of view.

16:06.532 --> 16:09.635 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Climate change was one of them.

16:09.668 --> 16:19.244 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I think that's part of
good and dependable
relations that we can speak
openly about our

16:19.278 --> 16:21.080 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
differences.

16:21.113 --> 16:25.651 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Does she believe
that the U.S.,
that this administration can
still be relied

16:25.684 --> 16:35.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on as a reliable partner to the
NATO nations
and to common values with the
European community?

16:35.427 --> 16:43.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER WITTIG: There are so many
trusted interlocutors
in this administration, minister
of defense,

16:43.869 --> 16:50.275 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Secretary Mattis, Secretary
Tillerson, the
national security adviser,
McMaster.

16:50.309 --> 16:52.911 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have had a lot of contacts
with them.

16:52.945 --> 16:55.280 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They reassured us on NATO.

16:55.314 --> 17:01.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They reassured us on the close
alliance with
our country and with the
Europeans.

17:01.320 --> 17:05.524 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, we have heard a lot of good
messages from
this administration.

17:05.557 --> 17:10.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So she absolutely
believes
the U.S. is committed to the
defense of NATO?

17:10.262 --> 17:16.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER WITTIG: This is what we
hear from many
important members of this
administration.

17:16.635 --> 17:18.470 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And we believe it.

17:18.504 --> 17:22.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I'm asking, of
course, because
the president has hammered away
time and again

17:22.474 --> 17:27.479 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at the amount of money the NATO
countries,
European countries are putting
into their

17:27.513 --> 17:28.547 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
own defense.

17:28.580 --> 17:31.283 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He tweeted again, President
Trump did yesterday.

17:31.316 --> 17:37.322 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He said, "We have a" -- he
mentioned the quote
in large capital letters --
"massive trade

17:37.356 --> 17:39.091 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
deficit," he wrote, "with
Germany.

17:39.124 --> 17:45.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Plus, they pay far less," again,
all caps,
"than they should on NATO and
military.

17:45.064 --> 17:46.899 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Very bad for U.S."

17:46.932 --> 17:51.203 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PETER WITTIG: The president
raises two important
points.

17:51.236 --> 17:55.574 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Fair burden-sharing in NATO, I
think that's
a valid point.

17:55.607 --> 18:02.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We are fully subscribing to the
decision of
the leaders of NATO in 2016 to
increase our

18:02.848 --> 18:08.687 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
spending, defense spending
incrementally in
a certain timeline.

18:08.720 --> 18:15.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What we reject is that when
people tell us,
you're not paying your
membership dues.

18:15.461 --> 18:16.495 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Yes, we are.

18:16.528 --> 18:19.898 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We are paying the common costs
for NATO.

18:19.932 --> 18:23.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But apart from that, there is
this pledge
to raise the defense spending.

18:23.435 --> 18:24.670 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And we're doing that.

18:24.703 --> 18:27.906 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have raised our defense
budget by 9 percent
last year.

18:27.940 --> 18:30.843 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Thank you very
much, Ambassador
Peter Wittig.

18:30.876 --> 18:31.844 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We appreciate it.

18:31.877 --> 18:32.845 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PETER WITTIG: Thank you, Judy.

18:32.878 --> 18:36.315 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It was a pleasure being here.

18:36.348 --> 18:48.660 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
