repeatedly called climate
change a hoax perpetuated by
China, tweeted

19:18.724 --> 19:23.395 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that his decision on the Paris
accord will
come over the next few days.

19:23.428 --> 19:26.698 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
For weeks, Mr. Trump has
signaled that he
would walk away from the deal.

19:26.732 --> 19:31.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He pledged to do so on the
campaign trail,
and has long argued that
environmental regulations

19:31.703 --> 19:33.005 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
cost American jobs.

19:33.038 --> 19:36.909 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: We're going to
cancel the Paris
climate agreement.

19:36.942 --> 19:41.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The president
also appointed
Scott Pruitt to lead the EPA, a
man who, in

19:41.547 --> 19:46.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the past, has sued to stop
environmental regulations
and who supports withdrawing
from Paris.

19:46.618 --> 19:48.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SCOTT PRUITT, Environmental
Protection Agency
Administrator: Paris is
something that we

19:48.787 --> 19:53.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
need to really look at closely,
because it's
something we need to exit, in my
opinion.

19:53.225 --> 19:55.060 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's a bad deal for America.

19:55.093 --> 19:59.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And in March,
the president
signed an executive order
undoing Obama-era

19:59.264 --> 20:01.133 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
climate change regulations.

20:01.166 --> 20:06.038 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Last week at the G7 summit, Mr.
Trump wouldn't
pledge to support the Paris
deal, a move that

20:06.071 --> 20:08.540 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
frustrated many European
leaders.

20:08.574 --> 20:13.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That sentiment was repeated
today by Jean-Claude
Juncker, the president of the
European Commission,

20:13.545 --> 20:17.883 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who strongly criticized the idea
of the U.S.
walking away from the agreement.

20:17.916 --> 20:21.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEAN-CLAUDE JUNCKER, President,
European Commission
(through translator): The
Americans can't

20:21.286 --> 20:23.922 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
just leave the climate
protection agreement.

20:23.956 --> 20:28.727 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, this notion, I am Trump, I
am American,
America first, and I'm going to
get out of

20:28.760 --> 20:30.562 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it, that won't happen.

20:30.596 --> 20:34.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The original
Paris accord
was signed by the Obama
administration, along

20:34.700 --> 20:38.604 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with 195 other countries, back
in 2015.

20:38.637 --> 20:43.675 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It voluntarily commits those
nations to decrease
their carbon emissions to try
and slow the

20:43.709 --> 20:45.577 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
rate of global warming.

20:45.611 --> 20:51.583 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The goal was to keep additional
warming below
2 degrees Celsius, or 3.6
degrees Fahrenheit.

20:51.617 --> 20:56.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many scientists argue that
warming beyond
that level could have serious
consequences,

20:56.188 --> 21:02.027 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
global sea level rise, increased
storms, heat
waves and droughts, and
potentially massive

21:02.060 --> 21:05.597 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
dislocation of people from
low-lying nations.

21:05.631 --> 21:09.134 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For months, President Trump has
been under
pressure from competing
interests.

21:09.167 --> 21:11.403 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: I'm hearing from a
lot of people
both ways.

21:11.436 --> 21:15.641 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The
president's daughter
and adviser Ivanka Trump emerged
as a supporter

21:15.674 --> 21:20.545 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the U.S. staying in the
agreement, the
same with Secretary of State Rex
Tillerson,

21:20.579 --> 21:24.383 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who argues withdrawing could
hurt U.S. negotiating
power.

21:24.416 --> 21:29.554 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tillerson's former company, oil
giant ExxonMobil,
joined a litany of other
companies who also

21:29.588 --> 21:32.057 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
urged the president to stay in
the deal.

21:32.090 --> 21:36.962 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Exxon described it as an
effective framework
to address the risks of climate
change.

21:36.995 --> 21:42.334 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But other voices urged
withdrawal, including
chief strategist Stephen Bannon,
as did 22

21:42.367 --> 21:46.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Republican senators, including
Majority Leader
Mitch McConnell, who said that
it was an important

21:46.938 --> 21:51.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
part of rescinding President
Obama's Clean
Power Plan, which has long been
the target

21:51.443 --> 21:53.679 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of Republican lawmakers.

21:53.712 --> 21:58.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Trump administration also
took aim today
at another rule covering
greenhouse gases,

21:58.417 --> 22:00.819 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
specifically emissions of
methane.

22:00.852 --> 22:05.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The EPA is now stopping an Obama
administration
rule that would cut down on
methane leaks

22:05.223 --> 22:08.627 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and pollution from oil and
natural gas wells.

22:08.660 --> 22:13.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But let's continue our look at
what's at stake
if the president opts out of the
Paris accord.

22:13.965 --> 22:18.637 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Michael Oppenheimer is a
professor of geosciences
and international affairs at the
Woodrow Wilson

22:18.670 --> 22:20.439 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
School at Princeton University.

22:20.472 --> 22:24.976 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He has been a longtime
participant in the
U.N. Panel on Climate Change,
which produces

22:25.010 --> 22:27.946 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
reports on the subject and won a
Nobel Prize.

22:27.979 --> 22:33.085 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Phil Kerpen is the president
of American
Commitment, a conservative group
opposed to

22:33.118 --> 22:34.186 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the Paris agreement.

22:34.219 --> 22:37.022 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Gentlemen, welcome to you both.

22:37.055 --> 22:40.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Phil Kerpen, I would like to
start with you
first.

22:40.359 --> 22:44.563 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We -- again, we still do not
know if the president
is going to walk away from this
agreement,

22:44.596 --> 22:46.031 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but it looks like he is going
to.

22:46.064 --> 22:47.299 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I know you agree with that.

22:47.332 --> 22:48.734 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So help me understand.

22:48.767 --> 22:51.370 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Make the best case why he should
leave Paris.

22:51.403 --> 22:54.106 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PHIL KERPEN, President, American
Commitment:
Well, I think the key point to
understand

22:54.139 --> 22:58.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is that the Paris treaty has no
discernible
impact on global average
temperature, and,

22:58.744 --> 23:01.079 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
therefore, the alleged climate
benefits are
illusory.

23:01.113 --> 23:05.917 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is an agreement that, if
every country
met its obligations, according
to the conventional

23:05.951 --> 23:09.521 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EPA model, it would reduce
global average
temperature less than two-tenths
of a degree

23:09.554 --> 23:11.022 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the year 2100.

23:11.056 --> 23:13.725 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, of course, these countries
are mostly
not meeting their obligations.

23:13.759 --> 23:17.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We just heard from Germany their
emissions
are up in each of the last two
years.

23:17.329 --> 23:19.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Philippines have already
withdrawn from
this agreement.

23:19.898 --> 23:23.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And India, which is allowed to
increase emissions
under this agreement, is
building too many

23:23.268 --> 23:24.603 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
coal plants to even meet their
target.

23:24.636 --> 23:26.505 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They are going to go well above
it.

23:26.538 --> 23:32.177 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.S. commitment would only
avert an increase
in temperature of about 15/1,000
of a degree

23:32.210 --> 23:33.912 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
by the year 2100.

23:33.945 --> 23:36.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, there is really not much
upside here,
but there is tremendous
downside, because

23:36.715 --> 23:41.420 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this agreement locks in those
EPA regulations
you were just talking about in
the introduction,

23:41.453 --> 23:45.657 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Clean Power Plan, which
increase electricity
prices about 25 to 30 percent.

23:45.690 --> 23:49.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That has a very negative impact
on consumers
across this country with no
benefit to show

23:50.028 --> 23:51.863 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
for it.

23:51.897 --> 23:56.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it also commits the American
taxpayer
to pay the lion's share of the
$100-billion-per-year

23:56.601 --> 24:00.005 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Green Climate Fund, a direct
wealth transfer
to the rest of the world.

24:00.038 --> 24:03.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I think the reason the
rest of the
world likes this deal so much is
that the

24:03.275 --> 24:07.913 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
United States cripples itself
economically
with regulations, and then it
pays the rest

24:07.946 --> 24:10.715 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the world for the privilege
of doing so
in increased foreign aid.

24:10.749 --> 24:12.117 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
To me, that is not leadership.

24:12.150 --> 24:14.419 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That is American losership.

24:14.453 --> 24:15.720 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And the president is right to...

24:15.754 --> 24:17.088 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

24:17.122 --> 24:18.924 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Let me get
Michael Oppenheimer
here on this.

24:18.957 --> 24:23.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A lot to unpack there, but the
substantive
criticism that even people who
favor the Paris

24:23.228 --> 24:26.498 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
agreement are, it is a voluntary
agreement.

24:26.531 --> 24:29.234 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There are no real binding
commitments.

24:29.267 --> 24:31.970 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Why do you think it is such a
greet deal that
we ought to stay in it?

24:32.003 --> 24:33.405 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL OPPENHEIMER, Professor
of Geosciences
and International Affairs,
Princeton University:

24:33.438 --> 24:36.408 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Paris agreement isn't
perfect, but it's
an important first step.

24:36.441 --> 24:40.612 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's why the statements of
Mr. Kerpen
are totally out of context.

24:40.645 --> 24:46.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, what is happening is
global emissions
of carbon dioxide have not
increased, in fact,

24:46.518 --> 24:50.622 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
decreased a little over the last
three years,
for the first time while the
global economy

24:50.655 --> 24:54.593 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was growing, because countries
are moving
to the new energy sources.

24:54.626 --> 24:59.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It would be foolish to pull out
of this agreement,
because, number one, it would do
great harm

24:59.865 --> 25:03.502 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to our relations with our allies
around the
world.

25:03.535 --> 25:10.942 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, secondly, it would condemn
the U.S.,
the world and future
generations, our own

25:10.976 --> 25:14.379 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
children, to a world with an
unacceptable
level of climate change.

25:14.412 --> 25:20.519 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if is a real pity, because
the Paris agreement
is the first time that all
countries of the

25:20.552 --> 25:27.092 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
world put plans on the table to
reduce emissions,
made commitments to reduce
emissions, including

25:27.125 --> 25:29.461 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
China, which is the world's
biggest emitter.

25:29.494 --> 25:30.962 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They are moving forward.

25:30.996 --> 25:33.398 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Not only are they moving forward
to reduce
their emissions.

25:33.431 --> 25:37.569 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're moving forward to make
money off the
new technologies.

25:37.602 --> 25:40.739 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are the world's leading
producer of solar
photovoltaic cells.

25:40.772 --> 25:44.075 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are the world's leading
producer of wind
turbines.

25:44.109 --> 25:49.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.S. is going to be left in
the dust if
we don't cooperate with other
nations to bring

25:49.114 --> 25:50.849 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
this threat under control.

25:50.882 --> 25:55.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I'm sure that President
Trump wants to
go down in history, but he
doesn't want to

25:55.287 --> 26:00.292 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
go down in history as the
president that condemned
the world to a dangerous climate
change.

26:00.325 --> 26:02.627 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Phil Kerpen,
let me ask
you about this.

26:02.661 --> 26:08.667 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is a very strong consensus
that if we
continue our current path of
fossil fuel use,

26:08.700 --> 26:12.971 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that there are going to be some
major implications
globally, not just here in the
United States,

26:13.004 --> 26:18.643 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
major economic blows, major
physical blows
to the planet we live on.

26:18.677 --> 26:20.845 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What do you argue we ought to do
about that?

26:20.879 --> 26:25.317 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PHIL KERPEN: Well, I think the
policies that
we have been pursuing in terms
of the fracking

26:25.350 --> 26:29.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
boom in the United States, the
dramatic increase
in gas production that shifted a
lot of our

26:29.154 --> 26:32.791 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
electric generation is really
what has driven
global emissions lower.

26:32.824 --> 26:36.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is United States' emissions
dropping pretty
dramatically that is actually
making up for

26:36.995 --> 26:40.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
other countries like Germany
that are increasing
with a heavy-handed regulatory
approach.

26:40.765 --> 26:46.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I think that we can have
an approach
that is not central economic
planning through

26:46.504 --> 26:51.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the EPA and we can continue to
develop lower
carbon energy sources, including
continuing

26:51.743 --> 26:55.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the gas boom, which I think is
going to be
the major driver of lower
emissions for the

26:55.080 --> 26:56.781 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
foreseeable future.

26:56.815 --> 26:59.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I don't know that we have
to necessarily
choose between those two things,
but I do

26:59.150 --> 27:04.456 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
know that an agreement that
imposes draconian
cuts on the United States, and
we take it

27:04.489 --> 27:09.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
seriously and implement in a
legally binding
way, while other countries make
promises,

27:09.427 --> 27:12.597 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
and then go ahead and do
whatever is in their
best economic interests, is not
one that serves

27:12.631 --> 27:17.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the United States well or
accomplishes those
climate-related policy goals
that people may

27:17.535 --> 27:18.770 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
state.

27:18.803 --> 27:21.106 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL OPPENHEIMER: Part of
what Mr. Kerpen
says is correct.

27:21.139 --> 27:24.476 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There has been a decrease, a
significant one,
in U.S. emissions.

27:24.509 --> 27:28.313 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that is partly due to the
penetration
of natural gas.

27:28.346 --> 27:32.917 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But a lot of the reduction in
emissions that
has come in the last few years
and is expected

27:32.951 --> 27:38.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to come in the future actually
arises from
a set of regulations that the
EPA promulgated

27:38.790 --> 27:40.925 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and which it carefully
calibrated...

27:40.959 --> 27:42.794 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

27:42.827 --> 27:46.498 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL OPPENHEIMER: Excuse me
-- that are
less than the cost of the
damages that climate

27:46.531 --> 27:48.199 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
change will bring.

27:48.233 --> 27:54.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, part of the regulations are
held up while
the courts decide their
legality.

27:54.272 --> 28:02.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But a critical aspect, the
regulation of motor
vehicle emissions -- which, by
the way, moving

28:02.080 --> 28:07.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to cars with high fuel economy,
helped saved
the industry during the
financial crisis -- those

28:07.952 --> 28:09.688 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
regulations are still in place.

28:09.721 --> 28:12.724 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so, in fact, is the Clean
Power Plan.

28:12.757 --> 28:15.393 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's the law until the courts
say it isn't.

28:15.427 --> 28:18.029 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Phil Kerpen,
can I ask you
a question about this?

28:18.063 --> 28:22.834 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are a lot of major U.S.
manufacturing
companies and energy companies.

28:22.867 --> 28:27.939 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
There's Exxon, Chevron,
Microsoft, Apple,
Johnson &amp; Johnson, Monsanto, Dow
Chemical

28:27.972 --> 28:31.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- I could go on and on -- they
all argue
that we should stay in the Paris
accord.

28:31.743 --> 28:35.346 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they make an economic
argument for staying
in there.

28:35.380 --> 28:39.050 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I'm just curious, don't you
find that
argument that they are making
persuasive?

28:39.084 --> 28:42.921 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These are not companies that
want to see American
industry hobbled in any way, and
they think

28:42.954 --> 28:44.689 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it is a good idea.

28:44.723 --> 28:48.059 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PHIL KERPEN: Well, I think large
incumbent
corporations always look full
advantage to

28:48.093 --> 28:49.861 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
protect themselves from new
innovative competitors.

28:49.894 --> 28:53.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that often comes in the form
of begging
for government regulation that
tends to lock

28:53.865 --> 28:58.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in market share by increasing
barriers to
entry and making it more
difficult for smaller

28:58.336 --> 29:02.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
companies that don't have armies
of compliance
officers and lawyers and
accountants to figure

29:02.340 --> 29:05.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out what I will pay, what the
thousands of
pages of paperwork that are
needed to be in

29:05.877 --> 29:07.612 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
compliance are.

29:07.645 --> 29:10.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so there is always this
incentive for
the largest companies that have
an army of

29:10.582 --> 29:13.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
lobbyists who want to make
themselves important,
an army of compliance officers
who want to

29:13.852 --> 29:17.756 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
make themselves important to use
that to lock
in their incumbency advantage.

29:17.789 --> 29:20.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that is why you have
seen all
of these large companies pushing
for that.

29:20.492 --> 29:23.828 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Michael
Oppenheimer, last
quick question to you.

29:23.862 --> 29:26.364 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Let's say that President Trump
decides to
pull out.

29:26.397 --> 29:28.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What is the impact?

29:28.199 --> 29:31.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Do you think that the other
countries will
continue with their pledges, or
do you think

29:31.569 --> 29:34.606 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that they will look and say hey,
look, the
U.S. isn't living up to this,
why should we?

29:34.639 --> 29:39.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL OPPENHEIMER: I think
what will happen
is some of the countries that
have just recently

29:39.477 --> 29:44.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
come around to making plans to
reduce emissions
will not pull out of the
agreement, but will

29:44.749 --> 29:49.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
peel off their commitments, and
it will reduce
the likelihood that the world
will move in

29:49.654 --> 29:52.323 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a safe direction on climate
change.

29:52.357 --> 29:55.293 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Furthermore -- but some
countries will keep
reducing their emissions,
because they're

29:55.326 --> 30:00.999 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
doing it for a variety of
reasons, including
protecting their air, like
China, which has

30:01.032 --> 30:06.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a bad air pollution problem, and
because,
as I said before, they want to
sell the new

30:06.171 --> 30:11.843 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
renewable energy technologies,
the clean technologies
everywhere, including the United
States, where

30:11.876 --> 30:13.945 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they are starting to push out
coal.

30:13.978 --> 30:21.553 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's hard for me to believe that
the U.S.
would subject itself to a less
favorable position

30:21.586 --> 30:23.354 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
economically.

30:23.388 --> 30:30.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After all, renewable energy now
has four times
as much employment in the U.S.
economy as

30:30.061 --> 30:31.629 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
does coal production.

30:31.663 --> 30:34.365 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Why are we looking to the past,
instead of
the future?

30:34.399 --> 30:35.466 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

30:35.500 --> 30:37.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: We have to go,
I'm sorry
to say.

30:38.002 --> 30:42.574 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Michael Oppenheimer, Phil
Kerpen, thank you
both very much.

30:42.607 --> 30:46.511 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PHIL KERPEN: Thank you.

30:46.544 --> 30:53.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL OPPENHEIMER: Thank you
for having
us.

30:53.451 --> 30:56.120 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

