38:52.730 --> 38:58.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATE ILIE: It took us months
before I actually
even saw her face, because she
had so many

38:58.202 --> 39:00.037 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
tubes in.

39:00.071 --> 39:04.275 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when your baby is in that
kind of situation,
it's almost like you can't let
your guard

39:04.308 --> 39:08.579 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
down to really bond with them,
because you're
scared of losing them.

39:08.612 --> 39:13.784 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Despite the
advances that
keep younger and younger preterm
babies alive,

39:13.818 --> 39:18.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
these kids are still at much
higher risk for
emotional, behavioral and
developmental problems

39:18.789 --> 39:20.725 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
later in life.

39:20.758 --> 39:25.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But a long-term study here at
Columbia University
Medical Center and New York
Presbyterian is

39:25.863 --> 39:34.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
testing if the simplest of human
interactions,
being calmed by mom, taking in
her smell,

39:34.672 --> 39:39.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
being soothed by her voice,
whether these
actions can somehow change the
development

39:39.777 --> 39:46.550 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
of these children by
strengthening their emotional
connection.

39:46.584 --> 39:49.553 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
The intervention is the
brainchild of Dr.
Martha Welch.

39:49.587 --> 39:51.422 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

39:51.455 --> 39:55.493 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MARTHA WELCH, Columbia
University: The brain
is developing at a very rapid
rate, especially

39:55.526 --> 39:58.429 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
at the end of pregnancy, in the
last trimester.

39:58.462 --> 40:05.870 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When the baby is born early, the
baby doesn't
have the same environment that
promotes that

40:05.903 --> 40:06.971 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
growth.

40:07.004 --> 40:11.142 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, in fact, the baby has the
opposite: isolation.

40:11.175 --> 40:16.480 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The child is bombarded with
sounds and light.

40:16.514 --> 40:21.285 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's antithetical to what the
brain needs
and the child needs for
development.

40:21.318 --> 40:27.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what we're doing is trying
to make up
for that to the greatest extent
possible.

40:27.425 --> 40:30.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: For the past
few months,
we have been following the Ilie
family and

40:30.961 --> 40:33.364 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
several others as they have gone
through this
study.

40:33.397 --> 40:37.435 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Elia Cardenas found it hard to
feel like a
mother in this clinical setting.

40:37.468 --> 40:43.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIA CARDENAS, Mother: How are
you supposed
to bond with the baby that's
behind a glass?

40:43.340 --> 40:48.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can only put your hand in
there and touch
them, but you can't hug them,
you can't hold

40:48.546 --> 40:50.247 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
them.

40:50.281 --> 40:53.851 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: But, in the
study, Cardenas
learned how to touch and connect
with her

40:53.884 --> 40:56.520 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
sons.

40:56.554 --> 41:01.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Miguelina Tavarez was taught
that a simple
cloth, one that smelled like her
and another

41:01.258 --> 41:08.232 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
that smelled like her
still-hospitalized daughter,
can calm both of them.

41:08.265 --> 41:13.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's called the family nurture
intervention,
and over 100 families have gone
through it.

41:13.737 --> 41:18.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
During the baby's stay in the
NICU, mothers
learn very simple nurturing
techniques, while

41:18.242 --> 41:20.077 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
researchers monitor their
progress.

41:20.110 --> 41:23.681 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL MYERS, Columbia
Psychiatry: The intervention
itself, I believe, has face
validity.

41:23.714 --> 41:25.015 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It just does make...

41:25.049 --> 41:26.016 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: It feels
right.

41:26.050 --> 41:27.852 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MYERS: It feels right.

41:27.885 --> 41:29.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: But Michael
Myers' job is
to measure if these
interventions do more

41:29.687 --> 41:31.388 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
than just feel right.

41:31.422 --> 41:36.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Do they make any substantive
long-term difference
to these children or their
mothers?

41:36.494 --> 41:43.434 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL MYERS: I'm the
challenger in chief
of ideas, to constantly make
sure that we

41:43.467 --> 41:46.003 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
don't accept what is intuitive
always as being
fact.

41:46.036 --> 41:49.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: For the past
five years,
the team has analyzed video
recordings of

41:50.007 --> 41:56.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
mothers and their children at
various developmental
stages, right after birth, four
months, 12

41:56.080 --> 42:02.953 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
months, 18 months, five years.

42:02.987 --> 42:09.760 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Their first randomized
controlled trial, with
115 moms and 150 infants,
indicate statistically

42:09.793 --> 42:16.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
significant results, among them,
a 36 percent
increase in brain activity in
the frontal

42:16.066 --> 42:17.835 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
region.

42:17.868 --> 42:20.304 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MYERS: Those brain
waves, that difference,
of about 40 percent, is really
visible.

42:20.337 --> 42:22.673 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's something that you can
really wrap your
head around.

42:22.706 --> 42:28.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: This activity
is in an area
associated with language,
thinking and emotional

42:28.345 --> 42:34.084 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
regulation, and, at 18 months,
babies in the
intervention showed improvement
in those areas.

42:34.118 --> 42:42.326 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Whether these changes last or
even continue
remains to be seen.

42:42.359 --> 42:46.931 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Results for mothers were also
significant,
improved caregiving in the NICU,
and, four

42:46.964 --> 42:52.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
months after giving birth, lower
levels of
anxiety and symptoms of
depression.

42:52.469 --> 42:57.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But convincing some about these
results may
have less to do with data than
with Martha

42:57.841 --> 42:59.843 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Welch's past work.

42:59.877 --> 43:04.582 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the 1980s, Welch wrote a book
called "Holding
Time," which counseled parents
to employ a

43:04.615 --> 43:07.785 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
very physical holding technique,
like you
see here.

43:07.818 --> 43:13.490 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The hope was that it would
increase communication
and emotional connection between
parent and

43:13.524 --> 43:15.392 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
child.

43:15.426 --> 43:20.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But some of Welch's ideas were
then co-opted
by other practitioners to
promote increasingly

43:20.431 --> 43:26.170 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
physical and coercive
techniques, similar
to this one seen in a CBS News
report.

43:26.203 --> 43:31.275 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: These earlier sessions were
designed
to force the rage out of him.

43:31.308 --> 43:35.245 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Another
session resulted
in the smothering death of a
10-year-old girl

43:35.279 --> 43:36.947 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
in 2000.

43:36.981 --> 43:41.619 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Welch says, even though her name
is still
associated with these
techniques, she had

43:41.652 --> 43:44.555 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
nothing to do with them and that
they have
damaged her reputation.

43:44.588 --> 43:45.990 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

43:46.023 --> 43:50.694 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARTHA WELCH: I was devastated
to be associated
in the press with them.

43:50.728 --> 43:57.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was very, very, very hurtful
to me, and
that upset lasted about 10
years.

43:57.801 --> 44:03.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Welch was also
criticized
for claiming that her nurturing
techniques

44:03.607 --> 44:09.113 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
can reduce the risk of autism,
which is something
premature babies are at greater
risk of developing.

44:09.146 --> 44:15.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Back in the late 1980s, with
just anecdotal
evidence, she said her holding
time techniques

44:15.786 --> 44:17.755 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
would reduce the risk.

44:17.788 --> 44:22.760 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And now she says her NICU
intervention has
shown, by one scientific
measure, to do the

44:22.793 --> 44:23.761 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
same.

44:23.794 --> 44:25.429 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

44:25.462 --> 44:29.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARTHA WELCH: About one out of
four babies
test positive for risk at 18
months.

44:30.000 --> 44:33.904 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have reduced that from one
out of four
to one out of 10.

44:33.937 --> 44:35.839 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
This is a big reduction.

44:35.873 --> 44:37.875 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: But others
aren't so sure.

44:37.908 --> 44:41.812 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
THOMAS FRAZIER, Autism Speaks:
My initial
reaction is really, I think it's
unlikely

44:41.845 --> 44:43.881 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that it protects children from
autism.

44:43.914 --> 44:47.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Thomas Frazier
is chief
science officer for Autism
Speaks, the national

44:47.985 --> 44:49.620 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
advocacy group.

44:49.653 --> 44:54.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He says there's persuasive
evidence that,
in many cases, autism emerges in
utero or

44:54.825 --> 44:59.563 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
very early in life, and he's
skeptical this
intervention could change that.

44:59.596 --> 45:04.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Frazier also worries this study
could inadvertently
cause some parents of autistic
children to

45:04.735 --> 45:06.537 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
blame themselves.

45:06.570 --> 45:10.641 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
THOMAS FRAZIER: There's an early
history within
autism of saying that parents
were sort of

45:10.674 --> 45:15.079 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at fault, right, if they had
just been more
nurturing, if they had just done
more, particularly

45:15.112 --> 45:20.350 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
moms, if they had just done more
to attach
to their children, that those
children somehow

45:20.384 --> 45:21.618 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
wouldn't have had autism.

45:21.652 --> 45:23.487 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We now know that that is just
not true.

45:23.520 --> 45:25.355 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

45:25.389 --> 45:29.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARTHA WELCH: The fact that
nurture is a remedy
doesn't mean that lack of
nurture was the

45:29.827 --> 45:31.929 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
cause.

45:31.962 --> 45:35.632 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Parents cannot blame themselves
for having
autistic children.

45:35.666 --> 45:37.401 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Almost every mother blames
herself.

45:37.434 --> 45:38.869 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
This is wrong.

45:38.902 --> 45:40.971 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But nurture is a remedy.

45:41.004 --> 45:45.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Meanwhile,
some of Welch's
scientific peers who were
skeptical this study

45:45.442 --> 45:51.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
would yield any positive,
lasting results
have been surprised by the
initial data, among

45:51.381 --> 45:52.783 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
them, Dr. Richard Polin.

45:52.816 --> 45:55.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He oversees the NICU where Welch
conducted
her trial.

45:55.452 --> 45:57.321 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

45:57.354 --> 45:59.990 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
RICHARD POLIN, Columbia
University: I was
skeptical that this kind of
intervention involving

46:00.023 --> 46:08.599 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
kangaroo, skin-to-skin care, and
smell and
other interventions would have
any long-term

46:08.632 --> 46:09.600 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
benefit.

46:09.633 --> 46:11.468 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I couldn't understand the
biological basis.

46:11.502 --> 46:14.805 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In fact, the biological basis is
still a little
uncertain to me.

46:14.838 --> 46:21.111 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, clearly, those kinds of
interactions
and bonding episodes have a
biological effect

46:21.145 --> 46:22.412 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on the baby's brain.

46:22.446 --> 46:25.983 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we hope it's a long-term
neurodevelopmental
change.

46:26.016 --> 46:29.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Additional
trials to see
if these results can be
replicated are now

46:29.653 --> 46:36.093 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
under way in New York and Texas,
with two
more in the works in New Jersey
and Florida.

46:36.126 --> 46:42.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Caroline Ilie, who was born at
just two-and-a-half
pounds, is now a year-and-a-half
old, and

46:42.065 --> 46:43.467 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
seems to be thriving.

46:43.500 --> 46:48.338 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Back home, all these mothers say
their families
are better off.

46:48.372 --> 46:53.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
While the science behind it
remains a mystery
to them, they think this
intervention strengthened

46:53.544 --> 46:58.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
their relationships during a
very fraught
period, with impacts they hope
will continue

46:58.949 --> 47:00.217 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
with time.

47:00.250 --> 47:07.191 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour" in New
York, I'm William
Brangham.

